g. We hear the voices of prostitutes and domestic slavegirls, immigrant wives of merchants, Christians and pagans, homemakers, and social activists alike. We read the stories of daughters who confronted cultural conflicts and racial discrimination; the myriad ways women coped with the Great Depression; and personal contributions to the causes of women's emancipation, Chinese nationalism, workers' rights, and World War II. The symphony of voices presented here lends immediacy and authenticity to our understanding of the Chinese American women's lives.This rich collection of women's stories also serves to demonstrate collective change over time as well as to highlight individual struggles for survival and advancement in both private and public spheres. An educational tool on researching and reclaiming women's history, Unbound Voices offers us a valuable lesson on how one group of women overcame the legacy of bound feet and bound lives in America. The selections are accompanied by photographs, with extensive introductions and annotation by Judy Yung, a noted authority on primary resources relating to the history of Chinese American women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChinese American womenxBiographyxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenxSourcesxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenxSourcesxSocial conditionsxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscovBiography. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryvSources. 0aChinese American womenzCaliforniazSan FranciscoxSocial conditionsvSources. 0aWomen immigrantsxSourcesxHistoryxCaliforniaxSan Francisco. 0aWomen immigrantszCaliforniazSan FranciscoxHistoryvSources. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2b